AB  - Consider the diffusion process defined by the forward equation u(t)(t, x) = 1/2 {xu(t, x)}(xx) - alpha{xu(t, x)}(x) for t, x >= 0 and -infinity < alpha < infinity, with an initial condition u(0, x) = delta(x - x(0)). This equation was introduced and solved by Feller to model the growth of a population of independently reproducing individuals. We explore important coalescent processes related to Feller's solution. For any alpha and x(0) > 0 we calculate the distribution of the random variable A(n)(s;t), defined as the finite number of ancestors at a time s in the past of a sample of size n taken from the infinite population of a Feller diffusion at a time t since its initiation. In a subcritical diffusion we find the distribution of population and sample coalescent trees from time t back, conditional on non-extinction as t -> infinity. In a supercritical diffusion we construct a coalescent tree which has a single founder and derive the distribution of coalescent times.
