AB  - In spatially structured populations, global panmixia can be viewed as the limiting case of long-distance migration. The effect of incorporating partial panmixia into diallelic single-locus dines maintained by migration and selection with complete dominance in an unbounded unidimensional habitat is investigated. The population density is uniform. Migration and selection are both weak; the former is homogeneous and symmetric; the latter is frequency independent. The spatial factor (g) over tilde (x) in the selection term, where x denotes position, is a single step at the origin: (g) over tilde (x) = -alpha < 0 if x < 0, and (g) over tilde (x) = 1 if x > 0. If alpha = I, there exists a globally asymptotically stable dine. For alpha < 1, such a cline exists if and only if the scaled panmictic rate p is less than the critical value /beta** = 2 alpha/(1-alpha). For alpha > 1, a unique, asymptotically stable dine exists if and only if beta is less than the critical value beta*; then a smaller, unique, unstable equilibrium also exists whenever beta < beta*. Two coupled, nonlinear polynomial equations uniquely determine beta*. Explicit solutions are derived for each of the above equilibria. If beta > 0 and a dine exists, some polymorphism is maintained even at x = +/-infinity. Both the preceding result and the existence of an unstable equilibrium when alpha > 1 and 0 < beta < beta* differ qualitatively from the classical case (beta = 0). (C) 2014 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.
